**Example 4.2**

Prove the following identities:

\[\begin{split}\text{(a)}&\frac{\sin\theta+\sin 2\theta}{1+ \cos 2\theta+\cos\theta}=\tan\theta.\\ \text{(b)}&\cos^{4}\alpha+\sin^{4}\alpha=\frac{1}{2} (1+\cos^{2}2\alpha).\\ \text{(c)}&\cot x+\tan x=\sec x\,\,\text{cosec}\,x. \end{split}\]

#### Solution:

To prove an identity, the strategy is to start from the more complicated side, and perform manipulation till we reach the other side.

\[\begin{split}\text{(a)}&\text{ LHS}=\frac{\sin \theta+\sin 2\theta}{1+\cos 2\theta+\cos\theta}\\ &=\frac{\sin\theta+2\sin\theta\cos\theta}{1+\left(2\cos^{2} \theta-1\right)+\cos\theta}\\ &=\frac{\sin\theta\big{(}1+2\cos\theta\big{)}}{\cos\theta\big{(}1 +2\cos\theta\big{)}}\\ &=\tan\theta\\ &=\text{RHS}.\end{split}\] \[\begin{split}\text{(b)}&\text{ LHS}=\left(\cos^{2} \alpha\right)^{2}+\left(\sin^{2}\alpha\right)^{2}\\ &=\left(\frac{1+\cos 2\alpha}{2}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{1-\cos 2 \alpha}{2}\right)^{2}\\ &=\frac{1+2\cos 2\alpha+\cos^{2}2\alpha}{4}+\frac{1-2\cos 2 \alpha+\cos^{2}2\alpha}{4}\\ &=\frac{1}{2}(1+\cos^{2}2\alpha)\\ &=\text{RHS}.\end{split}\] \[\begin{split}\text{(b)}&\text{ LHS}=\left(\cos^{2} \alpha\right)^{2}+\left(\sin^{2}\alpha\right)^{2}\\ &=\left(\frac{1+\cos 2\alpha}{2}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{1-\cos 2 \alpha}{2}\right)^{2}\\ &=\frac{1+2\cos 2\alpha+\cos^{2}2\alpha}{4}+\frac{1-2\cos 2 \alpha+\cos^{2}2\alpha}{4}\\ &=\frac{1}{2}(1+\cos^{2}2\alpha)\\ &=\text{RHS}.\end{split}\] \[\begin{split}\text{(c)}&\text{ LHS}=\frac{1}{\tan x}+\tan x\\ &=\frac{1+\tan^{2}x}{\tan x}\\ &=\frac{\sec^{2}x}{\tan x}\\ &=\sec x\left(\frac{\sec x}{\tan x}\right)\\ &=\sec x\left(\frac{1}{\cos x}\times\frac{\cos x}{\sin x}\right) \\ &=\text{RHS}.\end{split}\]

**Warning:**

To prove an identity, you must **NOT** begin by assuming that the identity is true, and then perform manipulation, such as,

\[\begin{split}\frac{\sin\theta+\sin 2\theta}{1+\cos 2\theta+\cos \theta}=\tan\theta&\Rightarrow\quad\sin\theta+\sin 2\theta=\big{(}\tan \theta\big{)}\big{(}1+\cos 2\theta+\cos\theta\big{)}\\ &\Rightarrow\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad\vdots\\ &\Rightarrow\quad\quad\quad\quad\quad 0=0.\end{split}\]

This is because you cannot use a result that has yet to be proven true.

